<chapter xml:id="ch-D" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Derivatives (D)</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        This module describes the conceptual development and computational development of the derivative. It contains nine learning targets:
      </p>
    </introduction>
      <dl>
        <li>
          <title>D1</title>
          <p>
            I can compute and interpret the average rate of change between two points, and describe its relationship to instantaneous rate of change
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>D2</title>
          <p>
            I can apply the definition of the derivative and use it to calculate, approximate, and interpret the derivative at a point or as a function
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>D3</title>
          <p>
            I can interpret the meaning of a derivative in context (with appropriate units)
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>D4</title>
          <p>
            Given a graph, I can sketch its derivative.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>D5</title>
          <p>
            I can graphically, numerically, or algebraically determine where a function is differentiable 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>D6</title>
          <p>
            I can apply shortcuts to determine derivatives of any order of the following types of functions: polynomials, exponentials, logarithms, trigonometrics, inverse trigonometrics
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>D7</title>
          <p>
            I can compute derivatives using one or more of the following rules or techniques: constant multiple, sum, difference, product, quotient, inverse
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>D8</title>
          <p>
            I can compute derivatives using the chain rule by itself and with other rules
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>D9</title>
          <p>
            I can use implicit differentiation to find the derivative of an equation
          </p>
        </li>
        <!--
        Taking D10 out for Fall 2024
        <li>
          <title>D10</title>
          <p>
            I can compute derivatives using logarithmic differentiation
          </p>
        </li>
      -->
      </dl>
  </objectives>
  
